### Describe the bug

Jwt Authentication using `JwtSecurityTokenHandler` will result an authenticated user all the time whenever any claim is provided, The user principal created is not null and it's identity has IsAuthenticated = true. There is no respect to `ValidationParameters.NameClaimType` nor `ClaimTypes.Name` or `ClaimTypes.NameIdentifier`

```csharp
[Fact]
        public void GenerateTokenAndUser_Success()
        {
            var id = "some-randome-id";
            var handler = new JwtSecurityTokenHandler();
            var text = new string('*', 64);
            var key = CreateKey(text);
            var claims = new[]
            {
                //this works right
                //new Claim(ClaimTypes.NameIdentifier, id),

                //but this is the wrong, it results: Identity.IsAuthenticated  = true, and Identity.Name = null
                //while Identity.IsAuthenticated should be false
                new Claim("wrong claim type", id)
            };

            var desc = new SecurityTokenDescriptor
            {
                Subject = new ClaimsIdentity(claims),
                Expires = DateTime.UtcNow.AddDays(1),
                SigningCredentials = new SigningCredentials(key, SecurityAlgorithms.HmacSha256Signature)
            };

            var token = handler.CreateToken(desc);
            var tokenString = handler.WriteToken(token);

            var valParameters = new TokenValidationParameters
            {
                NameClaimType = ClaimTypes.NameIdentifier,
                RequireExpirationTime = true,
                ValidateIssuer = false,
                ValidateAudience = false,
                IssuerSigningKey = key
            };

            var principal = handler.ValidateToken(tokenString, valParameters, out _);

            Assert.True(principal.Identity.IsAuthenticated == true);
            Assert.True(principal.Identity.Name == id);

        }
```

Having that, It defining policies in asp.net core became faulty, it is returning `Forbidden` all the time and will never return `Unauthorized` as long as there is any claim passed as you saw above. The only scenario to receive `Unauthorized` is when you don't have any claims.

```csharp
 services.AddAuthorization(options =>
        {
            options.AddPolicy(Policies.ClientPolicy.PolicyName, builder =>
                                builder.RequireAuthenticatedUser()
                                .RequireRole(Policies.ClientPolicy.Roles.IsClient));
        });
```

I think that is totally new bug, I never encountered something like before `.Net 6` and it is dangerous to consider any user with any valid claim as Authenticated!



### Expected Behavior

* User should NOT be authenticated if the token does not contain a claim with the type defined in `ValidationParameters.NameClaimType` 
* If User is is authenticated, then the identity.Name should never be null

### Steps To Reproduce

run the small unit test code I added above

